04427nam a22005895i 9780292789340DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212002txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927893407 a10.7560/7161622doi  a(DE-B1597)587638  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aF2538.P4784.D85 2002eb 7aHIS0330002bisacsh04a981.06/1/0921 aDulles, John W. F., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSobral Pinto, "The Conscience of Brazil" :bLeading the Attack against Vargas (1930-1945) /cJohn W. F. Dulles. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2002  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tPart I. Advocate of Order during the Old Republic (pre-1930) -- tPart II. Critic of Post-1930 Confusion (1931–1935) -- tPart III. Opponent of the Post-1935 Repression (1936-1938) -- tPart IV. In the Aftermath of the 1938 Uprisings (1938-1941) -- tPart V. Dealing with the Economia Popular and Matarazzo (1940–1944) -- tPart VI. Giving Attention to International Matters (1942-1943) -- tPart VII. Battling Cassiano Ricardo and the DIP(1943-1944) -- tPart VIII. Reacting to Catholic Conformity and Coriolano’s Repression (1944-1945) -- tPart IX. Emerging as a Hero with Brazil’s Return to Liberties (Early 1945) -- tPart X. Participant in Preparations for Elections (June–October 1945) -- tPart XI. Declining to Run for Congress and Explaining Vargas’ Fall (October 1945) -- tPart XII. Shocked by the Electorate’s Message (December 1945) -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPraised by his admirers as "one of those rare heroic figures out of Plutarch" and as "an intrepid Don Quixote," Brazilian lawyer Heráclito Fontoura Sobral Pinto (1893-1991) was the most consistently forceful opponent of dictator Getúlio Vargas. Through legal cases, activism in Catholic and lawyers' associations, newspaper polemics, and a voluminous correspondence, Sobral Pinto fought for democracy, morality, and justice, particularly for the downtrodden. This book is the first of a projected two-volume biography of Sobral Pinto. Drawing on Sobral's vast correspondence, which was not previously available to researchers, John W. F. Dulles confirms that Sobral Pinto was a true reformer, who had no equal in demonstrating courage and vehemence when facing judges, tribunals, and men in power. He traces the leading role that Sobral played in opposing the Vargas regime from 1930 to 1945 and sheds light on the personalities and activities of powerful figures in the National Security Tribunal, the police, the censorship bureau, and the Catholic Church. In addition to the many details that this volume adds to Brazilian history, it illuminates the character of a man who sacrificed professional advancement and emolument in the interest of fighting for justice and charity. Thus, it will be important reading not only for students of Brazilian history, but also for a wider audience dedicated to the crusade for human rights and political freedom and the reformers who carry on that struggle.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292789340423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292789340/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK